{"key":"processedPost-9046968","value":{"id":9046968,"first":9046918,"last":9047406,"when":1223483037,"utime":"10/08/08 07:23 PM","cleanedPost":"Below on the left is a picture I took through the lens of my zoom microscope of the area around my own fingernail when I was filming a contamination section for my DVD(which didn't make the cut due to running out of disk space on the 2 DVDs).&nbsp; I washed my hands with soap and water by scrubbing the area with a brush, then followed up with an alcohol wash before taking the picture.&nbsp; <br />The idea was to convince growers that they should wear latex gloves when doing inoculations or agar work, since you can never wash your hands well enough to remove the bacteria.<br />On the right is another picture through the lens of the zoom microscope of a ruby ear stud that I wear, only a few days after cleaning in an ultrasonic jewelry cleaner.&nbsp; As you can see, dead skin cells and bacteria infested slime from sweat build up within days.&nbsp; Again, the idea was to drive home the point to wear a surgical hair net that covers your ears when doing sterile work.&nbsp; If people would follow those simple solutions, plus use a surgical(not dust) mask, contamination from bacteria would be cut to almost nil.<br />We as cultivators are the number 1 vector of bacterial contamination in mushroom growing.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-007/160650891-fingernail_still_2.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-007/160650891-thumb_fingernail_still_2.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/08-41/348271114-Image30.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/08-41/348271114-thumb_Image30.jpg\"></a>"}}